The paper deals with automated sarcasm detection, which is a natural language processing task, hence it is likely to belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) category. The paper proposes a deep neural network architecture for sarcasm detection, which involves training a large number of parameters, making it relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) category. The use of dense connectivity in the network is a recent development in deep learning, which is relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) category. The paper also involves analyzing the dependency of prior convolution outputs, which is a topic in neural network optimization, making it relevant to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the performance of the proposed approach against state-of-the-art architectures, which involves comparing results and evaluating performance, making it relevant to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) category.
